You can example that file, and see the new h2o.init() which takes the same params as before, but does all the decisionmaking about existing clouds, creating clouds, parameters to h2o etc, outside of the test (no if decided_if_localhost)

h2o.py is a placeholder for indirecting to other files. I think it general tests will be modified to not require any additional stuff there (i.e. point to the new file directly)...but will see what feels right.

Ray has plans for how to expand h2o_methods.py to get autogen for h2o request params and returned json object.
All h2o requests are considered methods hanging off of h2o.nodes (which is really h2o_nodes.nodes)

So the concept, like h2o1, is a collection of nodes, which have some state (mostly reflecting how the java -jar was started..params..but other catchall state dumped in to). ....and then there are methods on the base H2O defintion

The full collection of objects (like h2o1) are: RemoteHost (only used if building multi-node with config json), LocalH2O, RemoteH2O, and ExternalH2O. These are all the same as h2o1.

Depending on what kind of node object you are, you have some method differences (same as h2o1)

I'm thinking I'll also have h2o_cmd() like before, for optional use, which is a functional api that calles the node level methods. (like existing h2o_cmd.runRF)

Note our R package already introduces a functional api that's different than the h2o node api (it tries to track existing R packages).

Make Indexer classes not inherit from tuple. (#1705)

* Make Indexer classes not inherit from tuple.

I'm not entirely sure this is a good idea. The advantage is that it ensures that
all our indexing code is entirely explicit: everything that reaches a backend
*must* be an ExplicitIndexer. The downside is that it removes a bit of
internal flexibility: we can't just use tuples in place of basic indexers
anymore. On the whole, I think this is probably worth it but I would appreciate
feedback.

Switch (some) coding/encoding in conventions.py to use xarray.coding. (#1803)

* Switch (some) coding/encoding in conventions.py to use xarray.coding.

The goal here is to eventually convert everything in xarray.conventions to
using the new coding module, which is more modular and supports dask arrays.
For now, I have switched over datetime, timedelta, unsigned integer, scaling
and mask coding to use new coders. Integrating these into xarray.conventions
lets us harness our existing test suite and delete a lot of redundant code.

Most of the code/tests is simply reorganized. There should be no changes to
public API (to keep this manageable for review). All of the original tests that
are still relevant should still be present, though I have reorganized many of
them into new locations to match the revised code.

Refactor string coding and fix string support in zarr (#2058)

* Move string coding from conventions to xarray.coding.

This refactor will make it easier to use different coding for different
backends.

It includes using a special dtype with metadata (like h5py) to identify
variable length strings. So in principle, we could now handle fixed width
and variable length unicode differently.

* Zarr backend roundtrips strings and bytes

* Add test validating that cf_decode() preserves dask string arrays.

* Fix failing test on python 2.7

Add virttest.staging.backports module

We'll have to stick with python 2.4 for a little while
yet, so let's bring autotest's backport module to virt-test.

This module contains some functions people have been
using to write their tests. In order to use them, you
can just make

from virttest.backports import all, bin, next

The module takes care of figuring out if there's a
builtin present, or if the backported implementation
has to be used.
